@node intro "Introduction"

SeekHTTP is a program, that searches in files for URLs.
You can choose between writing the URLs to a file, write to
standart outfile (see Config and Usage) or load them into
your browser. Currently supported browsers are iBrowse, AWeb
and Voyager. A CLI interface is also available. Available
languages are German, English and Portuguese. The file, where
the URLs are written in, is in HTML format.

@endnode

@node feat "Features"

Features of SeekHTTP:

   - Triton GUI
   - very fast
   - comfortable config program
   - as much inputfiles as you can (multiselect, when selecting
                                    inputfiles)
   - outputfile is in HTML format
   - loads your browser automatically and loads the outputfile
     in it (if you wish)
   - supported browser are iBrowse, AWeb and Voyager
   - CLI interface
   - a standart outfile, you can select an outputfile or use the
     standart outfile as outputfile
   - if the outputfile already exists, the URLs are appended to
     this file
   - support scripts for some programs to use SeekHTTP with them
   - available languages are English, German and Portuguese
   - easy to use, the GUI is self explaining
   - you can open SeekHTTP on any pubscreen
   - IT'S FREE!!! I DON'T WANT MONEY FROM YOU!

@endnode

@node req "Requirements"

You need:

- an AMIGA :)
- RexxMast running
- Rexxreqtools.library (available on aminet)
- Rexxtricks.library (available on aminet)
- tritonrexx.library (included)
- triton.library (for the tritonrexx.library, available on aminet)
- rexxapp.library (included)
- a file with URLs in it :-)

@endnode

@node install "Installation"

Copy SeekHTTP, SeekHTTPConfig, and RegisterSeekHTTP wherever you like, and run 
SeekHTTPConfig. Copy the "tritonrexx.library" and the "rexxapp.library" into 
your LIBS: dir.

@endnode

@node config "Configuration"

I have written a configprogram, for easier configuring and
keeping your old configs in new SeekHTTP versions.

Now, let's config:

Start it by double clicking on its icon,
and it should open its window.

Now follow these steps:

1. Select your language, available languages are English,
   German and Portuguese.

2. Select your browser, supported are iBrowse, AWeb and
   Voyager.

3. Select your browser executeable. You have two possibilities:
   1. Type the full path and the name of the executeable into
      the string gadget or
   2. Press the button after the string gadget, and a
      filerequester will pop up, where you can select the path
      to your browser and the browser executeable.

4. Type in path and name of the standart outfile. You can do this
   by pressing the button after the string gadget and select the
   outfile per filerequest. The standart outfile is used, when
   you use SeekHTTP from CLI and specify just an inputfile as
   argument, the standart outfile will be used as outputfile, or
   on gui, there is a frame called Save to, in this frame you can
   select between selecting a file as outputfile or using the
   standart outfile as outputfile. The standart outfile can be used
   as a base, where all urls are saved to, I have made a hotlist
   entry for the outfile in my browser.
   NOTE: You don't need to create a outfile by yourself, if the
         standart outfile doesn't exist, then SeekHTTP will create
         one.

5. Type in the pubscreen, where SeekHTTP will open its window on.
   If this screen doesn't exists, SeekHTTP will open its windows
   on the default pubscreen (Workbench).

6. Then, if you wish that your browser should start and load the
   outputfile when you use SeekHTTP from CLI, then check the checkbox
   after "Start Browser (CLI):".

7. Click on save to save your settings.


@endnode


@node use "Usage"

At first, when you enter an outputfile, that doesn't exists,
SeekHTTP creates it for you. You never need to create an
outpufile by yourself! (Hi Rodney! ;))

CLI usage:

to use SeekHTTP from CLI, without open the gui type in:
SeekHTTP <inputfile> [outputfile].

Fore example:
SeekHTTP RAM:Test.txt or
SeekHTTP RAM:Test.txt RAM:URLs.html

If you specify just an inputfile, the URLs will be written to
standart outfile (1st example), if you specify an outfile, the
URLs will be written into this file (2nd example).
When SeekHTTP is finished, a beep will be made. If you have
checked the "Start Browser" checkbox in the config program,
your browser will be started and the outputfile will be loaded
into your browser.


GUI usage:

If you run SeekHTTP without arguments, the gui will fire up.
Start SeekHTTP by typing in a shell:
SeekHTTP, or double click on its icon.
Then select the inputfile(s) in the filerequester and click on
"Ok". There is no limit, how much files you select and there is
no limitation, what filetype you choose. You can even select a
binary file, but the chance that you find URLs in a binary file,
are very low. :-)
TIP: Don't use HTML files, the results are not looking very good.

The "main" gui will open.

Explanation of the menu:

   Config...:
   Start configprogram, the new configs will not be used, when SeekHTTP
   is still running. They will be used when you start SeekHTTP the next
   time.

   Write to file:
   Same as the "Write to file" button in the gui.

   Send to browser:
   Same as the "Send to browser" button in the gui.

   Quit:
   Guess what this means. :-)

Explanation of the gui:

   Inputfile(s):
   A list, where all inputfiles without the path are displayed.


   Save to Frame:
   Here you can select the outputfile. If you select "Select file",
   a filerequester will open, where you can select the outputfile.
   If you select "Standart outfile", the URLs will be written to
   the standart outfile, that you (hopefully) have specified in
   the config program. (above things apply only if you select the
   "Write to file" operation)

   Browser frame:
   If you check the checkbox "Start browser?", SeekHTTP will do its
   job as normal and then start your browser and load the outputfile
   in it. (applies only if you selected "Write to file")

   Write to file:
   When you select "Write to file", the gui will close and a
   filerquester will open. In this filerequester you should select
   the outputfile, and then click on "Ok". If you have selected
   "Standart outfile" in the Save to Frame, no filerequester will
   open. When you have selected the outputfile, SeekHTTP will begin
   to work.

   Send to browser:
   When you select "Send to browser", the gui will close and SeekHTTP
   will begin to work. When it has done his job, your browser will
   be started and the outputfile (a tempfile, if you have selected
   "Select file" in the Save to frame or the standart outfile, if
   you have selected "Standart outfile") will be loaded into your
   browser, and SeekHTTP quits quiet.


Then a progressbar will open and tell you that you should wait.

When SeekHTTP is finished a requester will open, and tell you
that SeekHTTP is finished, and where the URLs saved to. You can
choose between "Quit now" and "New search".
Quit now:
   Try it. ;)
New search:
   Our old friend the inputfilerequester will open and the game restarts. :-)

If you have checked the "Start browser" checkbox:
After you have clicked on one of the two buttons, your browser
will come up and load the outputfile. 
(The above things apply only, when you have selected the "Write to file"
 operation!)

If you have selected "Send to browser":
Then no requester will appear that tells you that SeekHTTP is finished,
but your browser will be loaded and the outputfile (tempfile or standart
outfile) will be loaded into it.


Thats the whole usage!
I think it's easy, but I have written it. :-)

@endnode

@node script "Support scripts"

I have written some scripts to use SeekHTTP with them.

SHYAM:
A script for YAM.
Select a mail in YAM and start SHYAM. SHYAM will overgive the mail
to SeekHTTP, and SeekHTTP will search for urls in the mail.
The urls are written to standart outfile.

SHMD1.16:
A script for MicroDot 1.16. Select a message and start SHMD1.16.
The founden URLs will be written to standart outfile.
NOTE: This script doesn't work with MicroDot II! I'll wait for the
      release of MDII 1.0 before I try to write a script. 

If you have suggestions about other programs, send me a mail.

@endnode

@node hist "History"

V1.0 (sometimes in May):
 - first release

V2.0 (01-06-1998):
 - totally rewritten
 - support for Voyager and AWeb added
 - CLI interface added (thanx to John Pullicino)
 - requester what happens to the URLs (save, send to browser or both)

V2.1 (06-06-1998):
 - guide modified
 - if the outfile already exists, it is not overwritten, the URLs are
   appended to this file
   NOTE: if the URLs should be appended to a already existing file,
         the file MUST be a SeekHTTP generated file!!!

V2.2 (11-06-1998)
 - guide updated
 - multiselect added
   (I hope it works now!)

V2.22 (16-06-1998)
 - config program written
 - some internal changes in the script

V2.3 (25-06-1998)
 - config program rewritten and localized
 - SeekHTTP localized
 - some internal changes in SeekHTTP and SeekHTTPConfig

V2.5 (30-06-1998)
 - cli argument output file added
   if you don't specify an output file, the standard outfile
   that you have specified in the config program,
   will be used for saveing
 - the text in the requesters should be correct now.
 - goodies added

V2.6 (14-07-1998)
 - bug removed
   If a URL was in the middle of a sentence, the whole
   sentence was cut out and written to outfile. Now
   it works correct.
 - Portuguese translation of SeekHTTP
 - German translation of the guide

V3.0 (03-08-1998)
 - SeekHTTP rewritten
 - SeekHTTPConfig rewritten
 - guide rewritten
 - reqtools requester thrown away (except filerequest)
 - triton guis written
 - "both" function removed (is now the "Start Browser?"
   checkbox in conjunction with the "Write to file"
   operation)
 - progressbar added
 - ftp:// search added

V3.1 (21-08-1998)
 - bug removed
 - register tool added
 - pubscreen option added
 - SHYAM rewritten
 - Icons added
 - HTML Guide since V3.0 (sorry, I forgot that)
 - some other internal changes

@endnode

